^C@2You may need more information on "an opener" hand. Sure here is what Howard responded to my quarry.|CP|8|AT|

"Responder has to carefully evaluate his/her hand after getting the second bid from opener which is the third suit. Now, an opener hand is required plus other conditions for a FSF bid. Generally speaking, using the Rule of 20 to establish whether or not a hand is an opener is a good methodology and will work most of the time. However, based on the auction, you may upgrade some hands where you have a particularly good fit but ostensibly only invitational values or downgrade some hands that meet the rule of 20 where you have a bad fit. 

For example, if you have a hand with heart and club support and partner bids hearts and then clubs, you might decide a hand that is just short of an opening bid is still good enough (an opener) to bid game. Similarly, on the same sort of auction, if you have a 5/5 hand with spades and diamonds that meets the rule of 20, you might be concerned about a misfit and downgrade your hand a bit." |
